## Phase 7 — Improve loop (ONLY when `--improve`, `--auto`, or `--auto-fix` is set)

If `IMPROVE` is not set, STOP after Phase 6 — the run is complete. Everything
below runs ONLY when the fix loop is active (`--improve` interactive, or
`--auto` / `--auto-fix` unattended — Phase 0 forces `IMPROVE=1` for the auto
modes).

This is the one path where the skill causes a product-code change. It does so
ONLY through a **reviewed draft PR** that an eval has validated. It NEVER merges,
deploys, or pushes to a default branch. Iron Law #6 still holds for the analysis
itself; Phase 7 is an explicit, gated, opt-in extension.

**Two ways the human gates (7a, 7c) get satisfied:**
- **Interactive (`--improve`)** — `AskUserQuestion` as written below. Default.
- **Unattended (`--auto` / `--auto-fix`, `NONINTERACTIVE=1`)** — the `**Under
  --auto:**` sub-blocks REPLACE each `AskUserQuestion`. They are **fail-closed**:
  a finding reaches the build path only if it clears every guard; anything
  uncertain STOPS with no PR. Never call `AskUserQuestion` in these modes.
  Under `--auto` WITHOUT `--auto-fix`, 7c always defers — no PR is ever opened
  (analysis + archived investigation prompt is the deliverable).

The build/eval hard gates in 7d (before=FAIL/after=PASS, tests+typecheck green,
draft-only, never merge/ready) are IDENTICAL in every mode — the auto guards
only stand in for the human's *judgement* gates, never for the *proof* gates.

### 7a — Confirm scope (gate)

From the SURVIVING `needs-investigation` findings (Phase 5b), rank by the
Recommendations priority (P1 first). Present them and ask which to act on,
**defaulting to the single top finding** — do not act on more than the user
approves. Use AskUserQuestion:

- Re-ground: project = leadclaw MCP; window = last <N>d; this will spawn a
  fix-subagent that edits code and opens a DRAFT PR.
- List each needs-investigation finding (P-rank + one-line) as an option.
- Recommend: the top P1 finding only.
- Make clear: each selected finding = one subagent + one branch + one eval run +
  one draft PR. Default cap is 1.

If the user selects none / cancels: stop, report the analysis is done and no
improve action was taken. If there are zero needs-investigation findings, print
the loud headline:

```
NOTHING TO IMPROVE THIS WINDOW — 0 actionable (needs-investigation) findings.
No fix-subagent spawned, no PR. <one-line reason>.
```

and stop.

**Under `--auto` (`NONINTERACTIVE=1`) — no `AskUserQuestion`.** Replace the
prompt above with deterministic auto-selection (still cap 1, fail-closed):

1. Rank the SURVIVING `needs-investigation` findings by Recommendations priority
   (P1 first; tie-break by impact, then by the freshest major-change regression).
2. **Eligibility — every check must pass, or the finding is skipped:** it is
   `needs-investigation`, it carries evidence (Iron Law #1), and it is ranked
   **P1 or P2**. P3 (and lower) is NOT acted on autonomously.
3. Select the **single** top eligible finding. Cap 1 — never auto-build more
   than one finding per run, regardless of how many are eligible.
4. If NO finding is eligible (none survived, none P1/P2, or zero
   needs-investigation), emit the loud headline above and STOP — the report +
   archived investigation prompt is the complete deliverable. A quiet window is
   success, not failure; never lower the bar to manufacture a build.

Print which finding was auto-selected (P-rank + one-line) and why, so the run
log shows the choice a human would otherwise have made. Then continue to 7b.

### 7b — Investigate & plan (read-only subagent — NO code written yet)

The 7a gate picked WHICH finding. Do NOT jump straight to fixing. First spawn a
**read-only investigation subagent** (Agent tool, `isolation: worktree`) whose
ONLY job is to find the root cause and return a concrete BUILD PLAN — it must
NOT edit code, add files, or open anything. Prompt = the finding's Phase 5b
investigation prompt PLUS:

````
READ-ONLY. Do not edit, create, or delete any file. Do not branch, commit, or
PR. Your sole output is a build plan for a fix.

Investigate the root cause in leadclaw (grep the tool name under
packages/core/src/composite|tools/, read the code, live-probe if useful — test
creds are expendable). Then return a PLAN with EXACTLY these fields:
- ROOT CAUSE: the mechanism, with file:line.
- FILES TO CHANGE: each path + a one-line description of the intended edit.
- EVAL SCENARIO: the WORKFLOWS.md row you'd add (intent + scenario) to reproduce
  the bug, + any fixture needed.
- RISK: one-liner / minimal diff / redesign? blast radius? anything that could
  break adjacent behavior.
- CONFIDENCE + what you could NOT determine read-only.

Do not write code. The plan is the deliverable.
````

### 7c — Show the plan, get explicit approval (gate, before ANY code)

Surface the subagent's plan to the user in plain prose — ROOT CAUSE, the exact
FILES TO CHANGE (path + intended edit), the EVAL SCENARIO, RISK, and confidence.
This is the "tell me what you're going to build before you build it" gate: the
user sees the concrete change, not a hand-wavy recap.

Then AskUserQuestion: **A) Build this plan (recommended) B) Revise the plan
(say what to change → re-run 7b with the steer) C) Skip this finding
D) Cancel improve.** Write NO code until the user picks A. If the plan reveals a
redesign / cross-package change / data migration, say so and recommend Skip or
Revise. If confidence is low or the root cause is "couldn't determine read-only",
recommend against building.

**Under `--auto` (`NONINTERACTIVE=1`) — no `AskUserQuestion`.** A human's "build
this" is replaced by a fail-closed auto-approval guard. First: if `AUTOFIX` is
NOT set (plain `--auto`), ALWAYS defer here — the build path is off, no PR is
opened. Report the plan as `deferred to human: --auto-fix not enabled` and STOP
(the analysis + archived investigation prompt is the deliverable).

If `AUTOFIX=1`, auto-approve the plan and proceed to 7d **only when ALL of these
hold** (read them off the 7b plan):
- **CONFIDENCE is high** — abort on medium / low, or on "couldn't determine
  read-only".
- **RISK is minimal / contained** — abort on ANY of: redesign, cross-package
  coupling, data migration, schema/contract change, deleting or rewriting
  existing tests, or a large diff (more than ~3 files touched).
- **FILES TO CHANGE are tool-surface only** — every path under
  `packages/core/src/` or `packages/mcp/src/`. Abort if the plan touches config,
  CI, build tooling, or anything outside the tool surface.

If every guard passes → proceed to 7d exactly as the interactive path would
after the user picked A. If ANY guard fails → **abort the build for this
finding, open NO PR**, and report it as `deferred to human: <which guard
tripped>` (e.g. "confidence=medium", "risk: cross-package", "touches
.github/workflows"). Do NOT silently fall back to a different finding (cap-1,
fail-closed) — the archived investigation prompt already lets a human pick it up.

This guard replaces only the human's *judgement* call. The 7d *proof* gates
below — BEFORE-fix eval must FAIL, AFTER-fix eval must PASS, tests + typecheck
green, draft-only, never merge / mark ready — are UNCHANGED and still hard.

### 7d — Build & validate (only after plan approval, worktree-isolated)

Once the plan is approved, spawn the BUILD subagent (Agent tool, fresh
`isolation: worktree`) with the approved plan + this contract:

````
You are executing an APPROVED build plan in the leadclaw repo. Implement exactly
the approved plan — if you discover it needs to materially deviate (different
files, bigger scope), STOP and report rather than silently expanding.
You may edit code, add tests/scenarios, run the eval, archive the eval, and open
a DRAFT PR. You may NOT: merge, push to main, mark ready, or deploy.

Steps (in order; STOP and report if any can't be completed):
1. Branch off origin/main: ArtyETH06/mcp-fix-<slug>.
2. Add the eval scenario FIRST: add the WORKFLOWS.md row from the plan + any
   fixture. Note its workflow number N.
3. BEFORE/AFTER PROOF — establish the bug is real and the eval catches it:
   run `/eval --workflow N` on the UNFIXED code. It MUST FAIL (red). If it
   passes before any fix, the scenario doesn't actually reproduce the bug —
   STOP and report (a green-before-fix eval proves nothing).
4. Apply the fix from the plan (root cause, minimal diff).
5. `pnpm -r test` and `pnpm -r typecheck` MUST be green.
6. Eval-and-improve LOOP (max 3): run `/eval --workflow N`. PASS → step 7.
   FAIL → read output, revise the fix (not the scenario), re-run tests, eval
   again. Cap 3. Still failing after 3 → STOP, no PR, report every round.
   Never weaken the scenario to force green (anti-gaming) — STOP if tempted.
7. Archive the eval run: the /eval skill pushes its JSON to leadbay/mcp-dashboard;
   confirm that archive landed (or, if it didn't, push it / report why not).
8. Open a DRAFT PR (`gh pr create --draft`): body links the analysis finding,
   the BEFORE=FAIL / AFTER=PASS eval verdicts, and eval round count. Set
   assignee + a label + the Product project per repo convention.
9. SELF-REVIEW the PR you just opened, and close the loop on it:
   a. Run the `/review` skill against this branch (it does the adversarial
      Claude+Codex pass + fix-first classification + specialists). You are
      reviewing YOUR OWN fix — re-read the originating finding and confirm the
      diff actually resolves THAT finding, not merely that the eval is green.
   b. Apply ONLY the fixes `/review` classifies as AUTO-FIX (mechanical /
      low-risk). Do NOT apply ASK-class fixes (the judgment calls) — collect
      them into a list for the human instead. Never modify existing test files
      to apply a fix; add coverage in NEW files only (repo invariant).
   c. RE-PROVE GREEN after applying auto-fixes: re-run `pnpm -r test` +
      `pnpm -r typecheck` + `/eval --workflow N`. If an auto-fix breaks the
      eval or tests, REVERT that specific fix (don't loop trying to save it)
      and note it in the ASK list for the human. The eval staying green is the
      hard gate — a review fix never gets to regress the behaviour the PR fixed.
   d. Push the applied auto-fixes to the SAME draft PR. It stays DRAFT — never
      mark ready, never merge. Add a PR comment summarising: what `/review`
      auto-fixed, what it flagged as ASK (left for the human), and that the
      eval still passes.
   If `/review` is unavailable in this environment, skip 9 and say so in the
   report — do not fabricate a review pass.

Report (structured): branch, root cause (file:line), files changed, before-eval
verdict (must be FAIL), after-eval verdict + rounds, eval archived? (yes/where),
tests+typecheck result, draft PR URL (or why none), self-review verdict
(auto-fixes applied + count, ASK items left for human, eval still green after
review? yes/no), anything unverified. Never claim success you didn't observe.
````

### 7e — Collect + report (no auto-merge)

For each subagent, surface its structured report verbatim-ish:
- ✅ fix applied + eval PASS (in ≤3 rounds) + draft PR opened → give the PR URL
  and how many eval rounds it took. Also surface the **self-review** result
  (7d step 9): how many `/review` auto-fixes were applied, the ASK items left
  for the human to decide, and confirmation the eval is still green after the
  review fixes landed. If a review fix had to be reverted to keep the eval
  green, name it.
- ⚠ eval still FAILED after 3 improve rounds → no PR; show each round (what the
  eval caught + what changed) so the human decides. The loop converging-or-not is
  the signal; a non-converging fix needs a human, not a silent PR. (No
  self-review when there's no PR.)
- ✗ subagent couldn't locate a cause / blocked → report what it tried.

NEVER merge or mark ready. The human reviews every draft PR. If a subagent
returns `null` (died), report it and move on — do not retry silently.

**Under `--auto` / `--auto-fix`:** the structured report above IS the final
output — there is no human to read it back to. A finding that the 7c guard
deferred is reported as `deferred to human: <guard>` (no PR), alongside the
already-archived investigation prompt so a human can resume it. A `--auto` run
with no `--auto-fix` always lands here with zero PRs by design — that is the
expected Phase-A outcome, not a failure.

